      "content": "That's much more helpful for the framing I need. To round out the debate case, I need to address the economic/planning side of the argument. \n\nOn the debate floor, I'll be asked to defend the \"efficiency\" and \"stability\" of the zoning and redlining policies themselves. Could you elaborate on the argument that these neighborhood classifications provided a predictable environment for real estate investment and urban planning? Specifically, how would a proponent argue that creating racially distinct residential zones helped minimize property value volatility and ensured that specific neighborhoods remained \"stable\" or \"consistent\" for the people living there? I need to be able to articulate how these policies were framed as a way to bring order to urban growth and protect the long-term interests of the residents within those specific zones.",
